Step 1 - Prepare input data¶

This Python script will download the required input data and prepare it for the analysis. After this, run "Step 2 - Network analysis.ipynb" to generate the travel time matrices, then "Step 3 - Final analysis.ipynb" to complete the analysis and generate the visualizations.

In [1]:
import requests
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import numpy as np
import os
import shutil

Create regional county boundaries dataset¶

Download Shapefile containing county boundaries for all US states from the census bureau.

In [5]:
fileDir = os.path.normpath("./input_data/counties/")
zip_filepath = os.path.join(os.path.join(fileDir, "temp.zip"))
if not os.path.exists(fileDir):
    os.makedirs(fileDir)

r = requests.get("https://www2.census.gov/geo/tiger/GENZ2021/shp/cb_2021_us_county_500k.zip", stream=True)
with open(zip_filepath, 'wb') as f:
    for chunk in r.iter_content(chunk_size=128):
        f.write(chunk)

shutil.unpack_archive(zip_filepath, os.path.dirname(zip_filepath))

os.unlink(zip_filepath)

Read in the county data, extract only the counties in the Central Ohio region. Write the regional counties to a new file.

In [6]:
COUNTY_LIST = {
    "Delaware":"041",
    "Fairfield":"045",
    "Fayette":"047",
    "Franklin":"049",
    "Hocking":"073",
    "Knox":"083",
    "Licking":"089",
    "Logan":"091",
    "Madison":"097",
    "Marion":"101",
    "Morrow":"117",
    "Perry":"127",
    "Pickaway":"129",
    "Ross":"141",
    "Union":"159"
}

counties_all = gpd.read_file(os.path.join(fileDir, "cb_2021_us_county_500k.shp"))
counties_region = counties_all.loc[(counties_all["STATE_NAME"] == "Ohio") & (counties_all["COUNTYFP"].isin(COUNTY_LIST.values()))]
counties_region = counties_region.to_crs(epsg=4326)
counties_region.to_file("./temp_data/counties.shp")
ax = counties_region.plot(figsize=(10,10))

tracts_all = gpd.read_file("./input_data/tracts/tl_2021_39_tract.shp", dtype=object)
tracts_region = tracts_all.loc[(tracts_all["STATEFP"] == '39') & (tracts_all["COUNTYFP"].isin(COUNTY_LIST.values()))]
tracts_region = tracts_region \
    .filter(axis="columns", items=["GEOID", "COUNTYFP", "geometry"]) \
    .to_crs(epsg=4326)
tracts_region.to_file("./temp_data/tracts.shp")

Read in the block data and extract only the blocks that fall within the region.

In [10]:
blocks_raw = gpd.read_file("./input_data/blocks/tl_2021_39_tabblock20.shp", dtype="object")

blocks = blocks_raw.copy()

blocks = blocks.loc[blocks["COUNTYFP20"].isin(COUNTY_LIST.values())]
blocks = blocks \
    .rename(columns={
        "COUNTYFP20":"COUNTYFP",
        "GEOID20":"GEOID"
    }) \
    .filter(axis="columns", items=["GEOID", "COUNTYFP", "geometry"])

Download the 2020 decennial census population for each block from the Census API, remove the prefix from the GEOID, and rename the fields to more convenient names.

In [11]:
r = requests.get("https://api.census.gov/data/2020/dec/pl?get=GEO_ID,P1_001N&for=block:*&in=state:39%20county:{}".format(",".join(COUNTY_LIST.values())))
records = r.json()
columns = records.pop(0)
blockData = pd.DataFrame.from_records(records, columns=columns)

blockData["GEOID"] = blockData["GEO_ID"].apply(lambda x:x.split("US")[1])
blockData = blockData \
    .rename(columns={
        "county":"COUNTYFP",
        "P1_001N":"TOTALPOP"
    }) \
    .filter(axis="columns", items=["GEOID", "COUNTYFP", "TOTALPOP"])

Join the population data to the blocks feature class and write it to a Shapefile.

In [12]:
blocks = blocks \
    .merge(blockData, left_on="GEOID", right_on="GEOID") \
    .filter(axis="columns", items=["GEOID","COUNTYFP_x", "TOTALPOP", "geometry"]) \
    .rename(columns={"COUNTYFP_x":"COUNTYFP"})
blocks.to_file("./temp_data/blocks.shp")
blocks.head()

Create a rectangular grid of destination points¶

This will create a dense grid of points that fills the bounding box for the region. It will be used later to compute a travel time surface, which will ultimately be converted to isochrones. Note that these points will be snapped to the OSM street network in a later step.

In [14]:
GRIDSPACING = 0.02

bounds = region.total_bounds

xmin = bounds[0]
xmax = bounds[2]
ymin = bounds[1]
ymax = bounds[3]

x = np.arange(xmin, xmax, GRIDSPACING)

y = np.arange(ymin, ymax, GRIDSPACING)

X,Y = np.meshgrid(x,y)

points = gpd.GeoDataFrame(geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(X.ravel(), Y.ravel()))
points = points.reset_index().rename(columns={"index":"id"})

points.to_file("./temp_data/points_raw.shp")

ax = points.plot(markersize=0.1, figsize=(10,10))
region.plot(ax=ax, edgecolor="black", facecolor="none")

Download OpenStreetMap extract¶

The following block will download the OpenStreetMap extract for the State of Ohio. For other available extracts, see https://www.geofabrik.de/data/download.html.

In [15]:
fileDir = os.path.normpath("./input_data/")
if not os.path.exists(fileDir):
    os.makedirs(fileDir)

r = requests.get("https://download.geofabrik.de/north-america/us/ohio-latest.osm.pbf", stream=True)
with open(os.path.join(fileDir, "ohio-latest.osm.pbf"), 'wb') as f:
    for chunk in r.iter_content(chunk_size=128):
        f.write(chunk)
